Certainly! Imagine your Rust app is split into three object files: main.o, utils.o, and deps.o. The **linker** (such as `ld`) then combines all these bowls into a single, executable binary. Here's a very simplified mental model of what happens with code in Rust:

```rust
// main.rs
fn main() {
    print_hello();
}

fn print_hello() { println!("Hello!"); }
```
After compiling (`rustc -o main.o main.rs`) and generating all object files, the linker links them together into an executable.

Additionally, for dynamic linking, say you call a C library via FFI, the linker injects calls to that library so they work at runtime.
